Fig. 1
 displayed SEM images of BiOCOOH, 50% BiOCOOH/uCN, 4-CQDs/BiOCOOH/uCN and the EDS elemental mapping analysis. As depicted in the Fig. 1(a, b), BiOCOOH had a relatively ordered flower-like structure assembled from nanosheets. In Fig. 1(c), 50% BiOCOOH/uCN complex still retained the flower-like structure (the inset of (c)), and in the close-up view, many aggregates of uCN were immobilized on the BiOCOOH nanosheets, which could be deeply verified by TEM and HRTEM. Compared with 50% BiOCOOH/uCN, there is no significant morphologic change in 4-CQDs/BiOCOOH/uCN (Fig. 1(d)) due to the small size of CQDs [26]. The EDS elemental mapping of BiOCOOH exhibited that BiOCOOH consisted of Bi, O, and C elements (Fig. S2) and the EDS elemental mapping of 4-CQDs/BiOCOOH/uCN showed that the Bi, O, N and C elements were uniformly dispersed on the surface of 4-CQDs/BiOCOOH/uCN hybrid (Fig. 1(e-h)), which was compatible with elemental analysis (Table 1
). Therefore, it could be inferred that BiOCOOH and uCN have successfully coupled.
